      • register

        public static <T,​R extends T> Registration register​(R instance,
                                                          java.lang.Class<T> serviceInterface)
                                                   throws co.paralleluniverse.fibers.SuspendExecution
        Registers a class to make its methods available to be called on the EventBus. This method will wait until the class is ready to be contacted on the EventBus; i.e., once all its EventBus.consumer(String) have been registered.

        Conceptually, this is like registering an instance of a microservice; you can have multiple instance of the same serviceInterface, and the connect(Class) will send a request to one of the instance serving that serviceInterface.

        Vert.x provides the EventBus to enable communication between verticles (think Java beans) as a form of lightweight RPC. Vert.x's documented tools are tedious to use and engineering-wise, they are restricted in terms of the datatypes they can transfer across the network. This method instead provides a way to register a plain Java interface as the specification for the protocol a verticle would respond to over the EventBus.

        The registration function will register every non-static method specified in the interface with EventBus.consumer(String), specifying the address as:

        serviceInterface.getName() + "/" + method.getName();

        Internally, the system will use Serialization.serialize(Object) to serialize the message, which uses ObjectOutputStream to write the message (i.e., Serializable for serialization).

        The following is an example of how to use register(Object, Class). Typically you would register your service at the end of a verticle Verticle.start(Future) implementation. Suppose you are creating an Inventory service here: 

         
 // You need an RPC client to the cards service.
 RpcClient<Cards> cards;
 public void start() throws SuspendExecution {
     super.start();
     // Connect to the Cards service.
     cards = RPC.connect(Cards.class, vertx.eventBus());
     // Register this instance as a host serving the Inventory API.
     RPC.register(this, Inventory.class, vertx.eventBus());
 }
        Type Parameters:
        T - The service interface type.
        R - A concrete implementation of the service interface type.
        Parameters:
        instance - An instance of a concrete implementation of serviceInterface. This is a host for the service specified by serviceInterface on your cluster.
        serviceInterface - An interface with one argument non-default methods whose argument and return value are both implementing Serializable. This is your API.
        Returns:
        A registration that can be later unregistered with unregister(Registration)
        Throws:
        co.paralleluniverse.fibers.SuspendExecution
        See Also:
        for a way to get the address of a given method on the event bus.

      • connect

        @Suspendable
public static <T> RpcClient<T> connect​(java.lang.Class<? extends T> serviceInterface)
        Connects to the given serviceInterface on the EventBus and gives you an NetworkedRpcClient you can call methods on. Does not require the service to be running in order to be connected to.

        Internally, this method creates a Proxy instance that implements Rpc. When you call one of Rpc's methods, this proxy will EventBus.send(String, Object) a Serializable-serialized message to an address of the form:

        serviceInterface.getName() + "::" + method.getName();

        It will unpack the reply and give it back to you.

        Below is an example of using this method: 

         
 public void localMethod() throws SuspendExecution {
     // Connect to the Cards service. Typically you would do this in a start method of a verticle.
     RpcClient<Cards> cards = RPC.connect(Cards.class, vertx.eventBus());
     // Use the cards service. Note that we use "sync()" to idiomatically call this API "synchronously", in the
     // sense that continuations in Fibers are synchronous.
     GetCardResponse response = cards.sync().getCard(new GetCardRequest().withCardId("minion_boulderfist_ogre"));
 }
        Type Parameters:
        T - The type of the Java interface.
        Parameters:
        serviceInterface - The Java interface that corresponds to the API you're connecting to.
        Returns:
        An NetworkedRpcClient.

      • getAddress

        public static <T> java.lang.String getAddress​(java.lang.Class<? extends T> serviceInterface,
                                              co.paralleluniverse.strands.SuspendableAction1<T> methodCall)
        Gets an address from a named method call.

        For example, to get the address of an Accounts.createAccount(CreateAccountRequest) call, do: 

             
     RPC.getAddress(Accounts.class, accounts -> Accounts.createAccount(null));
        Note you can enter anything for the argument, and you don't need to do anything with the return value.

        Internally, this creates a proxy that implements the interface and sees which method you called.

        Type Parameters:
        T - The interface type.
        Parameters:
        serviceInterface - The service / interface
        methodCall - A lambda where you call the method on a fake instance of the service.
        Returns:
        A string corresponding to an EventBus address for this service method.
